phases.content:
Read `.tiki/research/reconciler-contract.md` first — the '#271 REVIEW decisions' section is the binding design. Modify `packages/framework/scripts/reconcile-state.mjs`:

1. Default fetcher `fetchIssueStateViaGh(number)`: spawnSync `gh issue view <number> --json state` with `shell: process.platform === "win32"`, `timeout: 5000`, encoding utf-8. Returns "OPEN" | "CLOSED" (uppercased from JSON .state) or null on ANY failure (non-zero, parse error, timeout, spawn error). Never throws.
2. Thread an options object through: `reconcile(tikiPath, { dryRun, fetchIssueState = fetchIssueStateViaGh })`. Inside the pass, ship-derivation for an entry runs ONLY when ALL of: entry not frozen; number not in history; `.tiki/plans/archive/issue-N.json` exists (archive presence wins even if an active plan also lingers). Only then call fetchIssueState(number) — this is the gh budget rule (SC4).
3. On "CLOSED": append an idempotent history record (state.mjs does not export its internals — implement the same shape locally: ensure `state.history.recentIssues` array, filter any prior record with the same number, unshift `{ number, title: entry.issue.title, completedAt: new Date().toISOString(), ...(entry.parentRelease ? { parentRelease: entry.parentRelease } : {}) }`). Then: standalone → `delete state.activeWork[workId]`, change action "ship-derived: removed"; parentRelease child → legality-pre-guarded applyTransition to completed/SHIP (phase null, parentRelease undefined-preserve), change action "ship-derived: completed". On "OPEN" or null → no change.
4. ORDERING in reconcileEntry: history check stays FIRST (unchanged); ship-derivation slots after it and BEFORE the in-flight artifact advance; an entry healed by ship-derivation must not also be advanced.
5. Amend the SAFETY CONTRACT header: rule 4 gains amendment 4a (#271) — completion may now ALSO be derived from archived-plan + gh-closed, with the budget + degrade-silently rules.

Tests (`packages/framework/__tests__/reconcile-state.test.mjs`; fake fetchers = plain functions with a call counter):
- standalone: archived plan + fake CLOSED → history gains record (assert shape incl. completedAt), entry removed;
- idempotent: history already has a record for N → no duplicate after heal;
- release child: archived plan + CLOSED + parentRelease → completed/SHIP, parentRelease preserved, history record carries parentRelease;
- TRAP: archived + fake OPEN → untouched; TRAP: NOT archived + CLOSED fetcher → fetcher NEVER CALLED and entry untouched (budget rule, SC4); TRAP: fetcher returns null (simulating gh failure) → untouched, pass exit normal, other entries still reconciled in the same pass;
- frozen: paused entry with archived plan → fetcher never called;
- call-count: a pass over a fixture with only in-flight entries (no archives) → fetcher call count 0 (SC4);
- dry-run: ship-derivation computes the change without writing.
Run `pnpm -C packages/framework test` — the dogfood-parity guard WILL be red until phase 2 regenerates (expected, same as #270 phase 1); all other tests must be green.

Same files as phase 1 plus the dogfood regen. Read the research doc's '#271 REVIEW decisions' for the binding scope.

1. Release reconciliation in the pass loop (currently `continue`s on non-issue keys — change to route `release:*` entries to a new `reconcileReleaseEntry(state, workId, entry, history, tikiPath)`):
   - skip frozen statuses (FROZEN_STATUSES applies);
   - version = entry.release?.version (skip if absent). `inReleaseHistory(history, version)`: match against history.recentReleases[].version;
   - (a) in history → `delete state.activeWork[workId]`, action "release: removed (in history)";
   - (b) NOT in history but def archived → archived def lookup must tolerate the v-prefix variance: check `releases/archive/<version>.json` and the toggled variant (add/strip leading 'v') — mirror check-release-readiness.mjs. Read the archived def (defensive parse); append release history record `{ version, issues: def.issues ?? entry.release.issues ?? [], completedAt: now, tag: version }` (idempotent: filter prior record with same version, unshift to history.recentReleases); then delete the entry, action "release: torn down (archived def)";
   - (c) otherwise in-flight → untouched.
2. buildReport: add release rows (recorded triple as-is; derived = the teardown verdict when (a)/(b) applies — render like the issue history rows: '(shipped → remove)' style — else derived = recorded, in-sync). Add issue ship-derivation rows: buildReport accepts the same `{ fetchIssueState }` options; for ship-shaped issue entries with a fetcher available and returning CLOSED, derived shows '(ship-derived → remove)' / completed; if the fetcher is unavailable or returns null, the row stays in-sync with note "archived plan; gh unavailable/open" — NEVER fabricated drift (SC5). --print main() passes the default fetcher.
3. Tests: release entry + version in history → removed; release entry + archived def (test BOTH v-prefix variants) + not in history → history reconstructed (assert issues list from def + tag) + removed; idempotent re-pass → no duplicate; in-flight release untouched; frozen (paused) release untouched; buildReport release rows (in-sync and teardown-derivable) + ship-derivation row with fake fetcher + read-only byte-unchanged assertion + fetcher-null row shows no drift.
4. Regenerate dogfood: `node packages/framework/install.js` from repo root; `git restore .claude/settings.json` if its diff is content-empty (line-ending churn).
5. LIVE-FIRE: from repo root run `node .claude/tiki/scripts/reconcile-state.mjs --print` — expect: issue:271 as a normal in-flight row (executing/EXECUTE 2/2, in sync per its own plan); ZERO would-create rows; ZERO ship-derived/release teardown rows (no archived plan exists for any active entry; there are no release:* entries). NOTE: --print with the default fetcher must make zero gh calls here because no entry is ship-shaped — if it hangs or calls gh, the budget rule is broken. Then a real pass `node .claude/tiki/scripts/reconcile-state.mjs` → expect changes []. Report both outputs verbatim.
6. Full `pnpm -C packages/framework test` — fully green including dogfood-parity.
